In [1]:

We read the data into a Dataframe and then transform it into a GeoDataFrame which is then projected to UTM 16N.

In [2]:
df = pd.read_csv("../data/processed/Cleaned_Chicago_Sales.csv")
gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, geometry=gpd.points_from_xy(df.Longitude, df.Latitude))
gdf = gdf.set_crs("EPSG:4326")
gdf = gdf.to_crs("EPSG:26916")

This is a common set of quantitiative variables shared across all of these models. We take a random sample of size 2.5% and ensure that it is the same 8,107 data points by seeding the random number generator with random_state=0.

In [3]:
i_vars = [
    'Age',
    'Bedrooms',  
    'Building Square Feet', 
    'Estimate (Building)', 
    'Estimate (Land)', 
    'Fireplaces', 
    'Full Baths',
    'Garage 1 Area',
    'Garage 2 Area', 
    'Half Baths', 
    'Land Square Feet',
    'Rooms',
    'Sale Quarter'
    ]
dep_var = ['Sale Price']
other_to_keep = ["PIN", "Neighborhood Code", "Town Code", "geometry"]
my_rows = i_vars+dep_var+other_to_keep
gdf = gdf[my_rows]
gdf = gdf.sample(frac=.025, random_state=0)
print("Dataframe has {} rows and {} columns".format(len(gdf), len(list(gdf.columns))))
X = gdf[i_vars].values
y = gdf[dep_var].values
gdf.head()

Dataframe has 8107 rows and 18 columns

Next, we create a list of the coordinates from the geometry.

In [4]:
coords = [ np.array((geom.xy[0][0], geom.xy[1][0])) for geom in gdf['geometry'] ]

Then we need to search for the optimal bandwidth to calculate GWR with and then run GWR with that bandwidth.

In [5]:
gwr_selector = Sel_BW(coords, y, X)
gwr_bw = gwr_selector.search()
print("Selected optimal bandwidth is:", gwr_bw)

There seems to be some issues with the GWR calculation as is evident by the Linear Algebra warnings and the huge parameter estimates for X0 (intercept) and X9 (Garage 2 Area). Looking at the model fit:

  • The adjusted $R^2$ of 0.74 is quite good compared to the other models.
  • The AIC and AICc of 12,134 and 12,142 are notably higher than the SEM and SLM-based models.

In [11]:
gwr_moran = Moran(gwr_results.resid_response.reshape(-1), w, permutations=199)
plot_moran(gwr_moran, zstandard=True, figsize=(10,4))
plt.show()

The residuals vs fitted plot shows a clear upward trend which may indicate problems with the model's fit. The Q-Q plot also shows that the residuals are not normally distributed. Lastly, the Moran's I of 0.07 is higher than any of the other spatial models although still considerably lower than OLS.

Below you can see the plots of the coefficients as they vary across space:

In [12]:
gwr_param_plots(gwr_results, gdf, names=["intercept"]+i_vars, subplots=(4,4), figsize=(20,30))

We can also mask out statistically insignificant parameters which is done by setting them to gray below. Interestingly, the intercept, Age, Estimate (Building), Estimate (Land) and Sale Quarter seem to have statistically significant values across most of the space while the other independent variables seem not to.
